============================================================
SECTION 1 — SYSTEM ARCHITECTURE
============================================================

ONX-1 uses a DUAL-LAYER COMPUTE MODEL:

LAYER 1 — REAL-TIME CONTROL (MCU)
- Deterministic execution
- <1 ms jitter requirement
- Direct actuator + sensor control

LAYER 2 — HIGH-LEVEL COMPUTE (AI)
- Sensor fusion (EKF)
- Vision processing
- Gait + terrain logic

SEPARATION RULE:
“Reflexes stay on MCU. Decisions live on AI.”

============================================================
SECTION 2 — PRIMARY COMPUTE (AI LAYER)
============================================================

MODULE:
- NVIDIA Jetson Orin Nano (8GB)

ROLE:
- Central processing unit
- Runs Linux-based AI stack

FUNCTIONS:
- EKF sensor fusion
- Terrain classification (CNN)
- Gait phase detection
- Motion intent estimation

INTERFACES:
- CSI (camera)
- UART (MCU communication)
- CAN (optional backbone)
- I2C / SPI (sensor bridge)

PERFORMANCE:
- ~40 TOPS AI compute
- GPU accelerated inference

POWER:
- 5V regulated input
- Peak draw: ~15W

COOLING:
- Active heatsink (fan)
- Integrated into torso cooling loop

============================================================
SECTION 3 — REAL-TIME CONTROL UNIT
============================================================

MCU:
- STM32H7 Series (400–480 MHz)

ROLE:
- Hard real-time control layer

RESPONSIBILITIES:
- Motor control loops (≥1 kHz)
- Encoder reading
- IMU polling (fast path)
- Safety monitoring
- Emergency shutdown execution

CONTROL METHODS:
- PID / torque control
- Feedforward compensation

EXECUTION ENVIRONMENT:
- Bare-metal or FreeRTOS

CRITICAL RULE:
NO actuator is directly controlled by Jetson

============================================================
SECTION 4 — COMMUNICATION ARCHITECTURE
============================================================

PRIMARY BUS:
- CAN Bus (recommended system backbone)

SECONDARY LINKS:
- UART (Jetson ↔ MCU)
- SPI (high-speed sensors)
- I2C (low-speed peripherals)

DATA FLOW:

SENSORS → MCU → Jetson
Jetson → MCU → ACTUATORS

MESSAGE TYPES:

1. STATE PACKET (MCU → Jetson)
   - Joint angles
   - IMU data
   - Foot pressure
   - System health

2. COMMAND PACKET (Jetson → MCU)
   - Target torque
   - Gait phase
   - Mode state

3. SAFETY PACKET (MCU internal)
   - Overcurrent
   - Overheat
   - Fault flags

============================================================
SECTION 5 — SENSOR FUSION (EKF)
============================================================

INPUTS:
- IMUs (helmet, torso, legs)
- Joint encoders
- Foot pressure (FSR arrays)

METHOD:
- Extended Kalman Filter (EKF)

STATE VECTOR:
- Position (x, y, z)
- Velocity
- Orientation (quaternion)
- Joint states

OUTPUT:
- Full-body pose estimation
- Stability vector
- Gait phase

EXECUTION:
- Runs on Jetson
- Update rate: 100–200 Hz

============================================================
SECTION 6 — VISION + TERRAIN SYSTEM
============================================================

CAMERA:
- CSI low-latency camera module

MODEL:
- Lightweight CNN (TensorRT optimized)

INPUT:
- Real-time video stream

OUTPUT CLASSES:
- Flat ground
- Incline
- Decline
- Stairs
- Uneven terrain
- Obstacle

RESPONSE:
- Adjust step height
- Modify torque profile
- Shift balance bias

LATENCY TARGET:
- <50 ms inference

============================================================
SECTION 7 — CONTROL LOOP SPEC
============================================================

MCU LOOP FREQUENCY:
- 1000 Hz (minimum)

LOOP STEPS:

1. Read sensors
   - Encoder
   - IMU (fast path)

2. Compute control
   - PID / torque

3. Apply actuator command

4. Check safety conditions

5. Send state packet to Jetson

JETSON LOOP:
- 100–200 Hz

JETSON STEPS:

1. Receive state data
2. Run EKF
3. Run terrain model
4. Compute desired motion targets
5. Send command packet

============================================================
SECTION 8 — POWER ARCHITECTURE
============================================================

INPUT:
- Battery pack (500–1000Wh Li-ion)

RAILS:

HIGH VOLTAGE:
- Motors (direct supply)

MID VOLTAGE:
- 12V rail (cooling, peripherals)

LOW VOLTAGE:
- 5V (Jetson)
- 3.3V (sensors, MCU)

REQUIREMENTS:
- Isolated rails (compute vs motors)
- EMI filtering mandatory

============================================================
SECTION 9 — SAFETY SYSTEM
============================================================

MANDATORY:

1. HARDWARE E-STOP
   - Cuts motor power immediately

2. WATCHDOG TIMER
   - MCU reset on failure

3. FAULT DETECTION:
   - Overcurrent
   - Overheat
   - Sensor failure
   - Communication loss

FAIL MODE:
- Immediate actuator disengagement
- Controlled system shutdown

